{
    "analysis": "We ran metric-based anomaly detection limited to the five candidate services and computed global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full series, then inspected the incident window for points exceeding each P95. Key findings from that metric scan: (1) ts-order-service shows the most significant anomaly: diskio with severity_ratio ≈ 3.02 (max ≈ 190,973 vs P95 ≈ 63,253) with 2 anomalous points (earliest 2024-01-23T23:32:00Z). ts-order-service also shows latency-90 exceedances (severity ≈ 1.36, earliest 23:47). (2) ts-auth-service shows moderate CPU and latency spikes (severity ~1.16–1.18 around 23:36 and 23:46). (3) Many memory KPIs on candidate services have only marginal exceedances (~1.00) and thus are less likely the primary cause. (4) ts-travel-service has an 'error' KPI with p95==0 and 25 in-window points but max==0 (likely a baseline-zero KPI; not directly actionable). These results indicate the strongest metric signal points to ts-order-service disk I/O spikes occurring ~23:32 UTC (and some latency spikes later). According to the diagnosis workflow, next we must use traces to localize among multiple faulty services at the same level (service layer) and to find the most downstream faulty service in call chains. Therefore we should analyze trace telemetry for the five candidate services: compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using full series, then find trace feature anomalies (value >= P95) within the incident window and report counts, earliest anomaly timestamp, max in-window and severity ratios to identify which service's traces show the strongest deviation and downstream impact.",
