    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. Restrict analysis to the five candidates: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P95 over the full available series (no time filtering). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window 2024-01-23 23:29:21 to 2024-01-23 23:59:21 UTC. For each candidate (cmdb_id, trace_name) count how many in-window points are >= P95, and for those series return one row with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95, count_anomalies_in_window, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc (ISO) or NaN, max_value_in_window (or NaN), severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / p95 (or NaN). Sort rows by count_anomalies_in_window desc then severity_ratio desc. Return up to top 20 rows. Use UTC when parsing timestamps."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps: \n- Metric analysis (full-series P95 then in-window check) for the five candidate services found strongest metric signals in ts-order-service: a disk I/O spike (severity_ratio ≈ 3.02, earliest anomaly 2024-01-23T23:32:00Z) and latency-90 exceedance (≈1.36, earliest 23:47). ts-auth-service showed moderate CPU and latency spikes (~1.16–1.18 around 23:36 and 23:46). Memory KPIs for candidate services showed only marginal exceeds (~1.00) and are unlikely primary. \n- Trace analysis computed global P95s for trace features but most trace error_rate P95s are 0.0 and in-window values are 0.0, producing many spurious \"anomalies\" due to zero baselines; thus traces did not provide meaningful directional evidence.\nWhat can be derived so far: ts-order-service exhibits the clearest, highest-severity anomalous metric (disk I/O) within the incident window around 23:32 UTC, with additional latency anomalies later. ts-auth-service shows moderate anomalies but lower severity. Since multiple service-level anomalies exist, we must now use logs to: (1) confirm whether ts-order-service shows error/warning log signals around the disk I/O spike, (2) check ts-auth-service logs for corroborating errors, and (3) inspect raw error logs for any explicit failure messages. This will help decide if ts-order-service disk I/O spike is the root cause or a symptom.\n",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv and error_logs.csv. Restrict to the five candidate components: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service. For log.csv: compute the global P95 for each (cmdb_id, log_name) using the full series (no time filtering). Then filter log.csv to the incident window 2024-01-23 23:29:21 to 2024-01-23 23:59:21 UTC. For each candidate (cmdb_id, log_name) report a row with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, p95, count_anomalies_in_window (points with value >= p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc (ISO) or NaN, max_value_in_window or NaN, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / p95 or NaN. Sort by count_anomalies_in_window desc then severity_ratio desc. Return up to top 20 rows. Additionally, from error_logs.csv filter to the same incident window and candidate components and return up to top 20 rows with columns: timestamp_utc (ISO), cmdb_id, message, sorted by timestamp asc. Use UTC when parsing timestamps."
}

